<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>SPECIAL NOTE REGARDING FORWARD-LOOKING STATEMENTS</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>This Form 8-K and other reports filed by us from time to time with the Securities and Exchange commission (collectively the &#147;<U>Filings</U>&#148;) contain or may contain forward-looking statements and information that are based upon beliefs of, and information currently available to, our management as well as estimates and assumptions made by our management. When used in the filings the words &#147;anticipate&#148;, &#147;believe&#148;, &#147;estimate&#148;, &#147;expect&#148;, &#147;future&#148;, &#147;hope&#148;, &#147;intend&#148;, &#147;likely&#148;, &#147;may&#148;, &#147;plan&#148;, &#147;positioned&#148;, &#147;project&#148;, &#147;should&#148;, &#147;strategy&#148;, &#147;will&#148;, &#147;would&#148; or the negative of these terms and similar expressions as they relate to us or our management with respect to future events and are subject to risks, uncertainties, assumptions and other factors (including the risks contained in the section of this report entitled &#147;Risk Factors&#148;) as they relate to our industry, our operations and results of operations, and any businesses that we may acquire. Should one or more of the events described in these risk factors materialize, or should our underlying assumptions prove incorrect, actual results may differ significantly from those anticipated, believed, estimated, expected, intended or planned. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Although we believe that the expectations reflected in the forward-looking statements are reasonable, we cannot guarantee future results, levels of activity, performance or achievements. Expect as required by applicable law, including the U.S. federal security laws, we do not intend to update any of the forward-looking statements to conform them to actual results. The following discussion should be read in conjunction with our pro forma financial statements and the related notes that will be filed herein.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>In this Form 8-K, references to &#147;we,&#148; &#147;our,&#148; &#147;us,&#148; &#147;our company,&#148; &#147;the Company,&#148; &#147;Tecton&#148; or the &#147;Registrant&#148; refer to Tecton Corporation, a Nevada corporation. &nbsp;&#147;Endurance&#148; refers to Endurance Exploration Group, LLC.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>1</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:2px; padding-top:4px; width:96px; border-top:2px solid #000000; border-bottom:2px solid #000000; float:left"><B>Item 2.01</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-top:4px; padding-bottom:4px; text-indent:-2px; border-top:2px solid #000000; border-bottom:2px solid #000000"><B>Completion of Acquisition or Disposition of Assets.</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; clear:left"><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>On December 31, 2013, Tecton Corporation executed a Share Exchange Agreement (&#147;SEA&#148;) with Endurance Exploration Group, LLC and its member owners, in which Tecton acquired one hundred percent (100%) of the membership interests in Endurance and, in exchange, the former members of Endurance received 20,550,539 shares of the Company&#146;s Common Stock. &nbsp;Endurance then became a wholly owned subsidiary of Tecton. &nbsp;Concurrent with the acquisition of Endurance Exploration Group, LLC the Company entered into a debt exchange agreement with its controlling Shareholder and principal creditor, Endeavour Cooperative Partners, LLC, (&#147;Endeavour&#148;) whereby approximately $291,000 of debt owed to Endeavour was exchanged for 12,733,496 shares of the Company&#146;s Common Stock. &nbsp;Additionally, options to acquire 5,000,000 shares of the Company&#146;s Common Stock at a price of $0.25 per share were issued to key personnel. </P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>On the execution of the Share Exchange Agreement our principal business became that of Endurance, which is more fully described below, and Endurance became our principal consolidated operating subsidiary. &nbsp;Endurance is a development stage company that specializes in subsea shipwreck research, search and survey, inspection, and recovery projects. </P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Since inception in 2009, we have evaluated over 125,000 shipwreck database entries and other sources to develop a &#147;High Interest&#148; list of approximately 400 shipwrecks and a &#147;Target List&#148; consisting of about two-dozen potential shipwreck projects; and, two of these &#147;Target List&#148; shipwrecks have moved to our operational phase, i.e. &#147;Operational List&#148;.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>In 2011, we began to purchase key mid-to-deep-water (500-2000 meter) survey and recovery equipment, including a 100 foot survey vessel, side-scan sonar equipment and a light work-class Remotely Operated Vehicle (&#147;ROV&#148;). Additionally, we began to develop a multi-year plan to conduct search and survey operations for some of our &#147;Target List&#148; shipwreck projects.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Relying on our research and methodical survey planning, in mid-2013, we began side-scan sonar search operations for our first project, &#147;<I>Sailfish</I>,&#148; a mid-19th century passenger liner sunk off the coast of New England carrying a gold shipment, and, we believe, highly likely, other passenger valuables. &nbsp;During the course of <I>&#147;Sailfish&#148;</I> operations to date, we have mapped and imaged, with side-scan sonar, approximately 700 square miles of ocean bottom searching for <I>&#147;Sailfish&#148;.</I></P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>In late 2013, we secured a three-year governmental contract from an East African nation granting Endurance Exploration Group permission to search for and recover the <I>&#147;Black Marlin&#148;,</I> a 17<SUP>th</SUP> century colonial-era trading vessel lost in the territorial waters of an island nation located in the Indian Ocean. &nbsp;Based upon our research and evaluation of the available historical record, we believe &#147;<I>Black Marlin</I>&#148; was carrying a sizable cargo of silver coinage and bullion for trade in the Far East. Our governmental contract also grants us rights to search for and recover secondary shipwreck targets in this country&#146;s territorial waters, and we have begun research on two potential secondary targets we call &#147;<I>Dolphin</I>&#148; and &#147;<I>Wahoo</I>&#148;.</P>
<P style="margin-top:5.533px; margin-bottom:5.533px; text-indent:96px" align=justify>Item 2.01(f) of Form 8-K states that if the registrant was a shell company, as we were, immediately upon the exercise of the SEA disclosed under this Item 2.01, then the registrant must disclose the information that would be required if the registrant were filing a general form for registration of securities on Form 10. Accordingly, we are providing such information below. Please note that the information provided below relates to the combined enterprises subsequent to the exercise of the SEA, except that information relating to periods prior to the date of the exercise relate respectively to the Company or Endurance as indicated. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>2</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><B><U>FORM 10 DISCLOSURE</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>ITEM 1&#151;BUSINESS</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Our Corporate History and Background</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>We were incorporated as a Nevada company on January 19, 2006, as a wholly-owned subsidiary of Hemis Corporation. &nbsp;On December 1, 2006, Hemis declared a dividend of Tecton shares to all shareholders as of that date and concurrently cancelled its share ownership in the Company. &nbsp;The effect of this dividend declaration and share cancellation was that Tecton was spun off as an independent company. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:24px" align=justify>Prior to June 2008, the Company was engaged in the exploration and acquisition of uranium properties that were either past producers or had been the subject of prior work programs and/or contained historic resources. On or about June 1, 2008, the Company ceased/discontinued operations of its uranium exploration activities; and, has incurred a net operating loss of approximately $37,000 since that period, as it has sought to restructure itself and find a suitable business opportunity. &nbsp;The Company has been deemed a &#147;shell company&#148;, as defined in the 1934 Securities and Exchange Act, Rule 12b-2 since the discontinuance of operations in 2008. &nbsp;During its restructuring period from June 2008 until December 31, 2013 the Company:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px">Elected a new slate of directors and appointed a new management team focused on finding a suitable business opportunity for the Company,</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>Attempted to reorganize its balance sheet through the US Bankruptcy courts by filing a Chapter 11 bankruptcy petition, but later withdrew its petition at the request of the court,</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>Brought current its filings with the State of Nevada and its financial reporting and disclosure filings with the US Securities &amp; Exchange Commission,</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>Effected a reverse 1 for 40 reverse split,</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>Amended and restated its Articles of Incorporation to increase the total authorized capital stock of the Corporation to 110,000,000 shares, being comprised of 100,000,000 shares of common stock with a par value of $.01 per share, and 10,000,000 shares of preferred stock with a par value of $.001,</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px">Exchanged approximately $291,000 of outstanding debt for 12,733,496 newly issued common shares, on December 31, 2013,</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>And, entered into a Share Exchange Agreement, on December 31, 2013, to acquire the ownership interests of Endurance Exploration Group, LLC for 20,550,539 newly issued common shares.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; clear:left" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:24px" align=justify>Our fiscal year end is December 31, and our common stock is quoted on the OTCQB electronic quotation system under the symbol &#147;TTNC&#148;.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B>Endurance Explorations Group, LLC</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>As detailed above in Item 2.01 of this current report, on December 31, 2013, the Company completed the purchase of 100% of the membership interests of Endurance Exploration Group, LLC, in exchange for 20,550,539 shares of Company&#146;s Common Stock being issued to the former members. Endurance is now a wholly owned subsidiary of Tecton with the operations of Endurance being the Company&#146;s primary focus. &nbsp;The members of Endurance who received the shares of stock included Micah Eldred and Carl Dilley, the current officers and directors of the Company.</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Endurance Exploration Group was formed in 2009 to explore, from an operational and financial perspective, the feasibility and potential economic return of recovering historic and modern day shipwreck cargos. We began by developing a research methodology with three goals. The first goal was to establish a comprehensive understanding of the larger economic, technological and social trends that lead to the transport of physical wealth across oceans during different historical periods, along with creating a </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&#147;High Interest&#148; list of shipwrecks and their cargos lost across various historical periods. &nbsp;Conflict, accidents and acts of nature claimed a percentage of all voyages, and many of the shipwrecked vessels are believed to have carried a valuable cargo. Our second objective was to identify, from this prior population of potential shipwreck losses, those shipwrecks that could be legally salvaged and recovered, and the cargos sold, with a positive return on the capital investment required for their location and recovery. &nbsp;Our third goal was to move those projects which had the potential to generate positive investment returns into an operational phase with a high, risk-adjusted, chance of success; and, to develop a portfolio of projects in various stages of research, search, survey and recovery. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>To that end, we began by evaluating historical shipwreck databases holding in excess of 125,000 entries as well as undertaking contextual and keyword library and archival searches. It is important to note that even these massive repositories of data reflect just a small percentage of the 3,000,000+ shipwrecks the United Nations estimates lay on the ocean floor.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>3</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>From these databases and other searches, we have developed an initial &#147;High Interest&#148; list of approximately 400 shipwrecks. Using criteria including (but not limited to) depth, potential search area, legal concerns, difficulty of excavation and potential value, we further culled the &#147;High Interest&#148; list to approximately two-dozen targets, the &#147;Target List&#148;. &nbsp;&nbsp;In order for a shipwreck to qualify for our &#147;Target List&#148;, and to potentially move forward as an &#147;Operational Target&#148; (&#147;OT&#148;) -one that we may consider for the search and survey operation phase- the shipwreck must possess the following criteria:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; float:left"><B>&#183;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify><B>Known Cargo of Value.</B> &nbsp;Based upon the historical and archival records, an OT must contain a quantifiable cargo of value. &nbsp;While the historical records may not provide our researchers with an exact present day value of a potential cargo, we must be able to determine a quantifiable &#147;range&#148; of its estimated value based upon cargo manifests or other archival documents.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; clear:left" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; float:left"><B>&#183;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify><B>Known Navigational Data</B>. &nbsp;Our research must provide information that would allow us to establish a geographically definable search and sinking location and, subsequently, an economically feasible search area for any potential target. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; clear:left" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; float:left"><B>&#183;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify><B>Legal Salvage and Clear Path to Title.</B> &nbsp;Admiralty law, salvage law, and various sovereign nation&#146;s laws and regulations concerning the search and salvage of historical and modern shipwrecks are complex. &nbsp;Prior to pursuing an OT, we must be able to establish a clear legal path to the title of any potential recovery, and search and recovery must be made in compliance with international laws and regulations or under specific country permissions.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; clear:left" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; float:left"><B>&#183;</B></P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify><B>Potential Returns Exceed Risk-Adjusted Cost of Search and Recovery.</B> &nbsp;&nbsp;Prior to moving a shipwreck from our Target List to an Operational Target, we evaluate a large number of factors to determine the potential search and recovery costs, and the risks associated with such search and recovery. &nbsp;Items considered include: a targets location and likely depth, its location from the nearest operational port, the complexity and costs of potential search and salvage, legal issues to title, and many other factors; and, we develop an initial search plan and budget for each potential project. &nbsp;We recognize the high risk, yet potentially high rewards, of our business; and, we realize that we will not be successful finding or salvaging every project we undertake. &nbsp;Therefore, prior to moving any project onto the &#147;Operational Target&#148; list, we take a risk-adjust approach to the potential returns that a project can provide; and we determine if, on a risk-adjusted basis, the potential target is economically feasible and appropriate to add to our portfolio of &#147;Operational Targets&#148;.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; clear:left" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>In 2011, we began purchasing key equipment for operations. Our equipment purchases have included a 100-foot survey vessel, tethered side-scan sonar units, and light work-class and inspection Remotely Operated Vehicles (ROV), &#147;Shackleton 1&#148; and &#147;Squirt&#148;.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Projects code-named &#147;<I>Sailfish</I>&#148; and &#147;<I>Black Marlin</I>&#148; have now reached operational or pre-operational status. For project &#147;<I>Sailfish</I>&#148; we have now surveyed over 700 square miles in the Western Atlantic Ocean in search of a sunken passenger liner carrying a substantial cargo of gold coinage. In addition to this manifest cargo, we also expect to find additional valuables among the personal stores of the ship&#146;s passengers. Please refer to <B>Current &amp; Ongoing Projects</B> for additional information.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>For project &#147;<I>Black Marlin</I>&#148; we have secured a three-year contract with a sovereign island nation in the Indian Ocean for the survey and recovery of a Colonial-era merchant vessel carrying silver. This contract also allows for other potentially valuable &#147;targets of opportunity&#148; within the territorial waters of this nation. Please refer to <B>Current &amp; Ongoing Projects</B> for additional information.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>We believe this survey and recovery capability combined with our proprietary research will allow us to conduct approximately two deep-water surveys per yearly weather window, should we have sufficient capital to undertake such operational surveys. </P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B><U>Description of Key Equipment &nbsp;</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px"><B><I>Survey Ship</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Our 100-foot survey ship has been recently refurbished to include a sonar winch and the latest in electronics and side-scan sonar survey equipment. Depending on the timeframe, circumstances and our other commitments, we may use this ship or charter another vessel of similar capability. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Sidescan Sonar</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Side-scan sonar is currently the industry-standard search methodology used for oceanic operations. &nbsp;An unmanned side-scan sonar unit, or &#147;towfish,&#148; is towed behind a manned surface vessel at a pre-set altitude above the seafloor. The sonar unit sends out a &#147;ping&#148; or sound-wave to acoustically map terrain, natural obstructions and man-made objects, including shipwrecks and jettison cargo. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>4</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>To engage in search operations, the Company has purchased side-scan sonar systems. Our dual-frequency systems may be set for a range of velocities, search widths and resolutions for both area mapping and high-resolution target prosecution up to 2,000 meters in depth. Our system is compatible with third-party hardware and software systems and meets IHO &amp; NOAA survey specifications. Beyond shipwreck surveys, the system is also capable of cable and pipeline surveys, channel conditioning, geophysical surveys, mine countermeasures and search and recovery operations. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>The Company&#146;s sonar systems are a flexible platform from both a hardware and software standpoint, and may continue to be upgraded with industry-standard, off-the-shelf sensor packages. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>The sonar &#147;towfish&#148; of one of our current survey systems was lost during the final days of our 2013 search operations. For more information on project &#147;<I>Sailfish</I>&#148;, please refer to <B>Current &amp; Ongoing Projects</B>. We expect to replace this sonar equipment and capability before beginning 2014 search operations.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Potential shipwreck targets found by sonar will be catalogued, evaluated and eventually visually prosecuted using the <I>Shackleton</I> <I>1</I> or <I>Squirt</I> ROV systems. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>ROV Shackleton 1</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>The Remotely-Operated Vehicle (ROV) system <I>Shackleton</I> 1 is a light work-class ROV. This system is comprised of underwater lighting, still and motion picture cameras and a single robotic manipulator arm. Initially designed for mid-water industrial applications, the ROV has been redesigned for shipwreck search, identification and cargo recovery operations. &nbsp;Beyond shipwreck operations, the system is also capable of cable and pipeline inspection and repair, geophysical sampling and search and recovery operations. &nbsp;ROV system &#147;Shackleton 1&#148; is currently undergoing the final stages of a complete disassembly and overhaul, and we expect to have it ready for the 2014 summer season. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><U>Employees</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>As of December 31, 2013, Tecton had three employees, none of whom serve full-time.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>As of December 31, 2013, Endurance had five employees, only one of whom serves full-time.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Other Employees and Contractors</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>We utilize contract personnel for vessel operation during our survey periods, and intend to continue to use contract technicians to perform marine survey and recovery operations in the future. From time to time, we have or intend to hire other contractors, subcontractors and consultants to perform specific services. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><U>Project Operations</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Research</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>During the Colonial period (1500-1850), the world economy was highly dependent on the physical transportation of bullion coinage, precious metals and high-value non-ferrous metals. A small percentage of shipping during this period was lost to storm, fire, acts of war, natural disasters and other causes, both known and unknown. The administration of this economic system required state-level bureaucratic oversight and record-keeping. Many of these historic records are available in publications, libraries, archives and digitized formats in depositories across the world. Though many records have been lost to time, enough remain to create in-depth, credible project profiles for potential excavation targets. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>To that end, Endurance Exploration Group has created a series of regional and period-specific databases from which to compare, evaluate and select potential targets for research, discovery and eventual excavation and recovery.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>The graphics below are a visual representation of selected world regions containing our &#147;High Interest&#148; database of shipwrecks and their approximate location and time of sinking.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>5</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><img src="super8ktectondjh2001.jpg" alt="[super8ktectondjh2001.jpg]" align=middle height=322 width=523></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><img src="super8ktectondjh2002.jpg" alt="[super8ktectondjh2002.jpg]" align=middle height=322 width=523></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>6</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><img src="super8ktectondjh2003.jpg" alt="[super8ktectondjh2003.jpg]" align=middle height=322 width=523></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><img src="super8ktectondjh2004.jpg" alt="[super8ktectondjh2004.jpg]" align=middle height=322 width=523></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Before search or recovery operations may begin, we seek to understand every factor necessary to mount a recovery operation with a high probability of success. </P>
<A NAME="_bclPageBorder62"></A><P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>7</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>These factors include, but are not limited to:</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>The historical context of the shipwreck, including political forces, technological developments, important contextual persons and events and the public reaction to the loss. </P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>Any images of the shipwreck, including still photography, motion pictures, drawing, paintings, recreations and/or models. </P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>A complete sinking timeline, including as much information as possible on weather patterns, departure date/time, intended course, course corrections, witness/observer statements. This includes any statement, fact or event material in any way to the sinking. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>A proposed search area with a high-probability of success, including an evaluation of all factors listed in the &#147;Sinking Timeline&#148; as well as any territorial boundaries or environmental factors. </P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>An Identification Guide, enabling rapid qualification or rejection of potential targets based on sonar and visual imagery, thus limiting expensive ship time on station.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>Cargo evaluation, evaluating the historical records on the target&#146;s cargo and potential modern-day value.</P>
<P style="margin-top:0px; margin-bottom:-2px; text-indent:24px; width:48px; font-family:Symbol; clear:left; float:left">&#183;</P>
<P style="margin:0px; padding-left:48px; text-indent:-2px" align=justify>Any encumbering factors, including territorial ownership of waters, insurance claims, potential cargo claims and sovereign rights. We will not being a project without a legal path to possession.</P>
<P style="margin:0px; clear:left" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>All of the above information is gleaned from publications, libraries, archives and digitized medium. Development of further projects is a continuous, ongoing process. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Search</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Most operational projects begin with a sonar search phase. We have outfitted our vessel with state-of-the-art sonar systems, an industry standard for underwater search operations. Our vessel tows the sonar systems to map the seafloor and search for targets. Potential targets are then selected from the sonar imagery using a combination of computerized post-processing and expert evaluation. While some shipwreck targets may be positively identified using high-resolution sonar system, others may need visual identification using an underwater camera ROV (Remote Operated Vehicle) system or an AUV (Autonomous Underwater Vehicle).</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Recovery</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Once a target is positively identified, excavation and recovery operations will begin using our &#147;Shackleton 1&#148; light-work class ROV system, or other chartered ROV systems. &nbsp;Shackleton 1 will document the site using sonar, still and motion-picture imagery. It will then be used for any necessary excavation, as well as coinage, bullion and/or other recovery operations. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Post-Recovery Conservation</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Coinage, precious metals and non-ferrous metals typically require a minimum amount of post-recovery conservation. In order to preserve the value of the recovered cargo, we will have an on-site facility capable of properly storing and transporting all recovered coinage, precious metals and non-ferrous metals to definitive and final conservation and storage prior to sale. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Sales</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>We intend to recover coinage and bullion precious metals, including but not limited to gold and silver. We believe that bullion metals, numismatically-graded coinage and non-graded coinage have significant value in the collector market. We intend to sell the existing independent coin dealers as well as directly to the collector and consumer market through the internet. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><U>Current &amp; Ongoing Projects &nbsp;</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Project &#147;Sailfish&#148;- Research Summary</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>The &#147;<I>Sailfish&#148;</I> was a steam-powered packet ship, part of a fast and indispensable transatlantic communication link, the perfect vessel to rapidly ferry mails and passengers between Britain and the United States. Large for her time, she was a side-wheel steamer constructed almost entirely of iron. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>On her last voyage, the &#147;<I>Sailfish&#148;</I> left Great Britain, bound for New York. She carried several dozen first-class passengers, more than four hundred steerage passengers and a full crew of nearly 130. The <I>&#147;Sailfish&#148; </I>&nbsp;also disembarked with a cargo of gold coins, and the Captain assumed a short, uneventful voyage to <I>New York. </I><FONT style="font-size:8pt"><I>(Sailfish&#146;s destination has been changed in this narrative to New York from her historical intended port of call) </I></FONT></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>8</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>When heavy seas set in, the <I>&#147;Sailfish&#148; </I>began to roll heavily. Though the initial problem was temporarily fixed, twelve hours later the same roll started again. Making matters worse, fire broke out. Buckets and pumps were manned, but the water rose rapidly and extinguished the furnaces, rendering the ship immobile. The fire quickly spread, driving the passengers above decks.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>The purser and two men attempted to rescue the gold shipment, but were driven back by the smoke and flames. A nearby ship came to the rescue, bravely maneuvering close to the <I>&#147;Sailfish&#148; </I>and running a line between the two to facilitate transfer of passenger. Per age-old protocol, the Captain was the last man off the ship.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Virtually nothing was saved. Nearly every trunk and stitch of clothing was lost, including all the money of the first-class passengers. Early the next morning, a passing ship fell in with the <I>&#147;Sailfish&#148;,</I> shadowing the stricken vessel through her final hours. The burning <I>&#147;Sailfish&#148; </I>exploded and sank by the stern, leaving only an overturned lifeboat, light portions of the decking and a few trunks. The passing ship spent an hour recovering debris, dutifully recorded the sinking position, and then sailed on to New York. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>We believe the &#147;<I>Sailfish&#148;</I> lies at a depth of between 200-500 meters of water.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Project &#147;Sailfish&#148; &#150; Current Status</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Side-scan sonar survey operations on Project <I>&#147;Sailfish&#148;</I> began in July of 2013, and continued through the summer weather window until September 2103. &nbsp;Over the course of this initial survey, approximately 700 square miles were digitally mapped. This sonar imagery was then post-processed and evaluated for potential targets. Our current plan of operations is to return for further sonar survey, target identification, and potential recovery work in the summer of 2014. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;The image below is of an unknown shipwreck found during our 2013 summer survey season. &nbsp;We do not believe this image to be that of <I>&#147;Sailfish&#148;, </I>but, rather, the wreck is believed to be a World War II-era shipwreck found during search operations. &nbsp;We expect to conduct visual ROV inspections of this and other sonar targets during the 2014 summer season.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><img src="super8ktectondjh2005.jpg" alt="[super8ktectondjh2005.jpg]" align=middle height=430.133 width=381.933></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Project &#147;Black Marlin&#148;- Research Summary</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>In the end of the 17th century, the world economy was fueled by the Spanish silver mines of the Americas, and the European demand for Asian drugs, spices, commodities and teas. This trade was based on the exchange of precious metals for goods, and silver was the only European payment acceptable to Asian trading partners.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=center>9</P>
<P style="margin:0px"><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; page-break-before:always" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>The <I>&#147;Black Marlin&#148;</I> was one such vessel engaged in this trade. She was an English East Indiaman, more than 700 tons, three decks high and armed with many cannon. In addition to the silver coin expected by Asian merchants, she also carried lace, golden fabric, beaver fur, tobacco, wine, cloth and iron nails.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>The shipping routes of the time took the English ship to the Indian Ocean for resupply in the middle of her long voyage to the East. Unknown her Captain and crew, nearby European enemy ships were hunting for English shipping. They discovered the <I>&#147;Black Marlin&#148;</I> was in the area and sailed to intercept. The European enemy ships approached the English ship under a false flag and prepared to attack.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>The trap set and ready to attack, the Europeans demanded the surrender of the English vessel. Instead of surrendering, the English captain counterattacked, and the vessels began to exchange heavy cannon fire, beginning a pitched fight that would continue over many hours. In a last-ditch effort to escape, the English ship unfurled her sails and attempted to sail away. The Europeans quickly caught up and soon the English ship was disabled and unable to continue fighting.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>Rather than surrender, the Captain of the English ship set his own vessel on fire, escaping in a small boat with a chosen group of men while allowing his own ship and abandoned sailors to burn. The fire reached the gunpowder storage, and the English ship exploded and sank, taking with her a rich cargo of silver.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>We believe this shipwreck lies at a depth of between 500-3000 meters of water.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Project &#147;Black Marlin&#148; &#150; Current Status</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>As of November 2013, Endurance Exploration Group finalized a contract with the sovereign government of an island nation in the Indian Ocean. The provisions allow for a three-year period in which to operate within the territorial and surrounding waters of the nation with full permissions to survey for and recover the <I>&#147;Black Marlin&#148;</I> and her silver cargo. Proceeds from recovery and sale are subject to a graduated distribution, with 100% first going to cover expedition costs and with a 70% / 30% split thereafter in the favor of Endurance Exploration Group. We expect to begin initial survey operations on project <I>&#147;Black Marlin&#148;</I> in mid to late-2014.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>As part of a larger economic development package included within our original proposal, we will also seek to develop media and museum products featuring both the treasure of the <I>&#147;Black Marlin&#148; </I>and the natural beauty of the island nation. </P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><I>Project &#147;Black Marlin&#148; &#150; Targets of Opportunity &#147;Wahoo&#148; and &#147;Dolphin&#148;</I></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>As part of discussions pertaining to project <I>&#147;Black Marlin,</I>&#148; Endurance Exploration Group has learned of two shallow-water &#147;targets of opportunity&#148; within the same territorial waters as the <I>&#147;Black Marlin.&#148; </I>Believed to be English East Indiaman, these wrecks (code-named &#147;Dolphin&#148; and &#147;Wahoo&#148;) remain unidentified at this time. Until these wrecks are identified, it will not be possible to generate any estimate on the potential value, if any. We expect to begin operations on these wrecks in conjunction with the <I>&#147;Black Marlin&#148; </I>in mid-2014.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><U>Patents, trademarks, licenses, franchises and concession</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;We currently own no patents, trademarks, or licenses; but have been granted governmental permissions for shipwreck search and recovery in the territorial waters of an East African island nation.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><U>Competition</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:61.067px" align=justify>There are a number of competing entities engaged in aquatic research, survey, inspection and the various aspects of the shipwreck salvage business. &nbsp;One or more of these competing entities may locate and recover a shipwreck that we intend to locate and recover. &nbsp;In addition, these competing entities may be better capitalized and may have greater resources to devote to their pursuit of shipwreck salvage.</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><B><U>Governmental and Environmental Regulation</U></B></P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR></P>
<P style="margin:0px; text-indent:48px" align=justify>The Company is subject to local, state and national taxation. Additionally, the Company&#146;s operations are subject to a variety of national, federal, state, local and international laws. In particular, the legal, political, or civil initiatives of countries, international governing bodies and/or other maritime jurisdictions may prevent, restrict, suspend or abort our operations. &nbsp;</P>
<P style="margin:0px" align=justify><BR>
<BR></P>
